article.headline: Oklahoma State 79, Texas A&M 77
article.story: STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) -- Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton told freshman Terrel Harris to look for his shot more. The result was a breakout performance and a crucial win for the Cowboys in their Big 12 home opener. Harris scored a career-high 21 points and had the tiebreaking three-point play to lift Oklahoma State to a 79-77 win against Texas A&M on Wednesday night. "Tonight was just a night that I was hitting my shots. I got my opportunities, so I just ran with it," Harris said. "I still played the same defense the same way. I just had the shots to come with it this time." Harris, who'd averaged only 6 minutes before entering the starting lineup four games ago, hit a driving jumper with 2:24 left and his ensuing free throw gave Oklahoma State (11-5, 1-1 Big 12) a 77-74 lead. Torre Johnson answered a jumper by A&M's Acie Law IV to restore Oklahoma State's lead to three, and Kenneth White and Joseph Jones each missed 3-pointers that would have tied the game for Texas A&M (11-2, 1-1). After a free throw by Chris Walker, the Aggies got one last chance when Jamaal Brown's pass to Harris went out of bounds with 22 seconds left, but Law missed a 3-pointer from the top of the key at the buzzer. "I thought I had a pretty good look," said Law, who ended up with the ball after the first two options on the designed play failed. "It just didn't fall for me." Law scored a career-high 35 points to lead the Aggies, who have lost both of their road games this season. Joseph Jones added 27 points. A&M coach Billy Gillispie said the play was designed to get the ball inside, but his team did a good job taking what Oklahoma State was giving up. "I'd take that shot every single time to win a game on the road against a good team," Gillispie said. "I thought it was in, especially the way he had played tonight. It just didn't go in." The Cowboys got 16 points from Mario Boggan, 12 from Johnson and 11 from JamesOn Curry and were able to respond to several A&M runs in the second half. Texas A&M rallied to take the lead with a 15-2 spurt started by layups by Walker and Antanas Kavaliauskas. Law had seven points during the run, including a fast-break layup that gave the Aggies a 54-47 lead. The advantage stretched to eight after Jones' three-point play, but the Cowboys used an 11-3 run to tie the game at 60 on Boggan's two free throws with 9:27 left. Law then scored the Aggies' next seven points and his driving layup to extend the Aggies' edge to 67-62 before the Cowboys charged back again. Oklahoma State regained the lead on Curry's free throw with 4:07 to play that made it 70-69. It was the first of five back-and-forth lead changes leading up to Jones' free throw that tied it at 74. Harris, who had hit only two 3-pointers in Oklahoma State's first 15 games, made 4 of his 6 shots from 3-point range. He hit three straight 3-pointers to put the Cowboys up 9-5 to start the game. "I try not to let that affect me, but since I did hit it, it really did affect me," Harris said. "It gave me a lot of confidence to where I felt like I could hit every shot that I put up." Sutton said Harris entered preseason camp looking like the best shooter on the team, but then developed a hitch in his shot that caused him to leave the ball short. He'd seen Harris improving in practice over the past few days. "I thought Terrel was terrific," Sutton said. "We knew he was capable of doing it," Johnson said. "Coming off the bench seeing him hit those first three shots, I knew he was ready to play and hit the open shots. He was ready to shoot. "Coach had been on him all week about him not being ready to shoot when the guards penetrate and dish, so he was ready, he got in the pocket and knocked his shots down." The Cowboys, who haven't lost to the Aggies in Stillwater since the 1922-23 season, have won 12 straight and 18 of 19 in the series. "I'm happy we won," Sutton said. "It would have been tragic to lose a game here at home like that."
